---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Ionospheric Models">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics">Mathematics</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Ionospheric Models</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Mathematics · Article 4 of 5</span>
        <h1>Ionospheric Models</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          The ionosphere is the largest single error source in single-frequency GNSS — up to
          100 metres in extreme conditions. Dual-frequency receivers eliminate it algebraically.
          Single-frequency receivers must model it. This article explains the physics of
          ionospheric delay, how the Klobuchar and NeQuick models work, and how the
          ionosphere-free combination removes it entirely.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>10 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#physics">The physics of ionospheric delay</a></li>
          <li><a href="#tec">Total Electron Content (TEC)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#mapping">The mapping function</a></li>
          <li><a href="#klobuchar">Klobuchar model (GPS)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#nequick">NeQuick model (Galileo)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#iono-free">The ionosphere-free combination</a></li>
          <li><a href="#higher-order">Higher-order effects</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="physics">The physics of ionospheric delay</h2>
      <p>
        The ionosphere is a region of the atmosphere between approximately 60 km and 1,000 km
        altitude where solar ultraviolet and X-ray radiation ionises gas molecules, creating
        a plasma of free electrons and ions. This plasma is a <strong>dispersive medium</strong>
        — it slows the group velocity of radio waves (the code pseudorange signal) while
        advancing the phase velocity (the carrier phase).
      </p>
      <p>
        The refractive index of the ionosphere for a signal at frequency f is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">n ≈ 1 − 40.3·N_e / f²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          N_e = electron density (electrons/m³) · f = signal frequency (Hz)<br/>
          The refractive index is less than 1 — the phase velocity exceeds the speed of light
          (this is allowed; information travels at the group velocity, not the phase velocity).
          For GPS L1 at 1575.42 MHz with N_e = 10¹¹ electrons/m³:
          n ≈ 1 − 1.62×10⁻⁶ — a tiny but precisely measurable effect.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Integrating the refractive index along the signal path gives the ionospheric delay
        on the code pseudorange:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">I = ∫(1 − n)·ds = 40.3/f² · ∫N_e·ds = 40.3·TEC/f²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          I = ionospheric delay on pseudorange (m) · TEC = ∫N_e·ds = Total Electron Content
          (electrons/m²) along the signal path · f = frequency (Hz)<br/><br/>
          Key result: ionospheric delay is proportional to TEC and inversely proportional to
          frequency squared. This 1/f² dependence is what enables dual-frequency correction.
          The carrier phase experiences an equal and opposite advance: Φ_iono = −I/λ cycles.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Physics visual -->
      <div class="diagram-wrap">
        <div class="diagram-label">Ionospheric effect on code vs carrier</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 180" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr7" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="8" refY="5" markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M2 1L8 5L2 9" fill="none" stroke="context-stroke" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- Satellite -->
          <circle cx="60" cy="30" r="10" fill="var(--accent)" opacity="0.8"/>
          <text x="60" y="16" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">Satellite</text>
          <!-- Ionosphere layer -->
          <rect x="0" y="60" width="680" height="40" fill="rgba(251,191,36,0.08)" rx="0"/>
          <text x="340" y="84" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#fbbf24" font-family="var(--sans)">Ionosphere (60–1000 km)</text>
          <!-- Receiver -->
          <rect x="560" y="120" width="60" height="30" rx="4" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="590" y="139" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--sans)">Receiver</text>
          <!-- Signal path -->
          <line x1="68" y1="38" x2="558" y2="122" stroke="var(--accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="5 3" marker-end="url(#arr7)" opacity="0.7"/>
          <!-- Code delay annotation -->
          <text x="250" y="55" font-size="11" fill="#ff4757" font-family="var(--sans)">Code: delayed (slower group velocity)</text>
          <!-- Phase advance annotation -->
          <text x="250" y="130" font-size="11" fill="var(--accent)" font-family="var(--sans)">Phase: advanced (faster phase velocity)</text>
          <!-- Same magnitude -->
          <text x="340" y="162" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--sans)">|I_code| = |I_phase| — equal magnitude, opposite sign</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="tec">Total Electron Content (TEC)</h2>
      <p>
        TEC is the key ionospheric quantity — the line integral of electron density along the
        signal path. It is measured in TECU (Total Electron Content Units):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">1 TECU = 10¹⁶ electrons/m²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          1 TECU of TEC causes approximately 0.162 m of delay on GPS L1 (1575.42 MHz)
          and 0.267 m on GPS L2 (1227.60 MHz).<br/><br/>
          Typical TEC values:
          1–5 TECU at night at mid-latitudes (minimal delay, ~0.2–0.8 m on L1),
          10–50 TECU during daytime at mid-latitudes (1.6–8 m on L1),
          50–200 TECU at equatorial latitudes near solar maximum (8–32 m on L1).
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tec-table">
        <div class="tt-row tt-header">
          <span>Condition</span>
          <span>TEC (TECU)</span>
          <span>L1 delay</span>
          <span>L2 delay</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tt-row">
          <span>Night, mid-latitude</span>
          <span>1 – 5</span>
          <span class="good">0.2 – 0.8 m</span>
          <span class="good">0.3 – 1.3 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tt-row">
          <span>Day, mid-latitude</span>
          <span>10 – 50</span>
          <span class="warn">1.6 – 8 m</span>
          <span class="warn">2.7 – 13 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tt-row">
          <span>Equatorial, solar max</span>
          <span>50 – 200</span>
          <span class="bad">8 – 32 m</span>
          <span class="bad">13 – 53 m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="tt-row">
          <span>Geomagnetic storm</span>
          <span>up to 400+</span>
          <span class="bad">up to 65 m</span>
          <span class="bad">up to 107 m</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="mapping">The mapping function</h2>
      <p>
        TEC is typically modelled in the <strong>vertical</strong> direction above the receiver.
        A signal to a satellite at elevation angle el passes through more ionosphere than a
        vertical signal — the slant path is longer. The <strong>mapping function</strong>
        converts vertical TEC (VTEC) to slant TEC (STEC):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">STEC = VTEC · MF(el)</div>
        <div class="formula">MF(el) = 1 / √(1 − (R_E · cos(el) / (R_E + h_IPP))²)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          R_E = Earth radius (6371 km) · h_IPP = ionosphere shell height (typically 450 km)<br/>
          el = satellite elevation angle<br/><br/>
          At el = 90° (zenith): MF = 1.0 (shortest path)<br/>
          At el = 10°: MF ≈ 3.0 (three times more ionosphere)<br/>
          At el = 5°:  MF ≈ 4.5 (four and a half times more)<br/><br/>
          This is why low-elevation satellites have much larger ionospheric errors — and why
          elevation masks matter. An elevation mask of 10° keeps MF below ~3.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The point where the signal path pierces the ionospheric shell is called the
        <strong>Ionospheric Pierce Point (IPP)</strong>. Ionospheric corrections and models
        are referenced to IPP coordinates, not the receiver position.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="klobuchar">Klobuchar model (GPS)</h2>
      <p>
        The Klobuchar model (1987) is broadcast by GPS in the navigation message as 8 coefficients
        (α₀–α₃ and β₀–β₃). It models the ionospheric delay as a half-cosine function that
        peaks at 14:00 local time and uses a constant night-time value:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">I_v(t) = ⎧ 5×10⁻⁹ + A·cos(2π(t − 50400)/P)   if |t − 50400| &lt; P/4</div>
        <div class="formula">         ⎩ 5×10⁻⁹                              otherwise</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          I_v = vertical ionospheric delay (seconds) at the IPP<br/>
          t = local time at IPP (seconds of day, 0–86400)<br/>
          A = amplitude = Σ αₙ · φ_mⁿ (φ_m = IPP geomagnetic latitude in semicircles)<br/>
          P = period = Σ βₙ · φ_mⁿ (clamped to minimum 72,000 s)<br/>
          50400 s = 14:00 local time (peak of the cosine)<br/>
          5 ns (5×10⁻⁹ s) ≈ 1.5 m at L1 (night-time floor)<br/><br/>
          Convert from seconds to metres: I_m = I_v × c × MF(el).
          The Klobuchar model corrects approximately <strong>50% of the RMS</strong>
          ionospheric delay — better than nothing, far worse than dual-frequency.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="klobuchar-shape">
        <div class="ks-title">Klobuchar delay profile over one day (typical mid-latitude)</div>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 180" width="100%" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <!-- Grid -->
          <line x1="60" y1="20" x2="60" y2="150" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <line x1="60" y1="150" x2="640" y2="150" stroke="var(--border)" stroke-width="0.5"/>
          <!-- Y axis labels -->
          <text x="50" y="24" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">10 m</text>
          <text x="50" y="72" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">5 m</text>
          <text x="50" y="154" text-anchor="end" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">0 m</text>
          <!-- X axis labels -->
          <text x="60" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">00:00</text>
          <text x="190" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">06:00</text>
          <text x="330" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">14:00</text>
          <text x="450" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">18:00</text>
          <text x="640" y="168" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">24:00</text>
          <!-- Night floor left -->
          <polyline points="60,143 190,143" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Cosine peak centred at 14:00 (x=330) -->
          <path d="M190,143 Q240,143 260,100 Q290,40 330,22 Q370,40 400,100 Q420,143 450,143" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Night floor right -->
          <polyline points="450,143 640,143" fill="none" stroke="var(--accent2)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <!-- Fill under curve -->
          <path d="M190,150 L190,143 Q240,143 260,100 Q290,40 330,22 Q370,40 400,100 Q420,143 450,143 L450,150 Z" fill="rgba(0,153,255,0.08)"/>
          <!-- Peak label -->
          <text x="330" y="16" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--accent2)" font-family="var(--mono)">Peak ≈ 10 m</text>
          <!-- Night label -->
          <text x="120" y="137" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="var(--text3)" font-family="var(--mono)">1.5 m (night)</text>
        </svg>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Klobuchar correction quality:</strong> The model was designed to correct 50%
          of the RMS delay at mid-latitudes. It performs poorly near the equatorial anomaly
          (±15° magnetic latitude) where the ionosphere is most variable and structured.
          During geomagnetic storms it may actually make things worse. Despite its limitations,
          it is free, simple and available to all GPS receivers worldwide.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="nequick">NeQuick model (Galileo)</h2>
      <p>
        Galileo uses the <strong>NeQuick-G</strong> ionospheric model, an adaptation of the
        NeQuick 2 research model. It is more physically realistic than Klobuchar because it
        models the full 3D electron density profile of the ionosphere — not just a single
        shell approximation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Galileo broadcasts 3 coefficients (a₀, a₁, a₂) that define an effective ionisation
        level parameter <em>Az</em>:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">Az = a₀ + a₁·μ + a₂·μ²</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          μ = modified dip latitude at the receiver (related to magnetic inclination)<br/>
          Az is clamped to [0, 400] TECU and used as input to the NeQuick-G algorithm,
          which numerically integrates the electron density profile along the signal path
          to compute STEC directly — no mapping function required.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="model-compare">
        <div class="mc-row mc-header">
          <span>Property</span>
          <span>Klobuchar (GPS)</span>
          <span>NeQuick-G (Galileo)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>Broadcast coefficients</span>
          <span>8 (α₀–α₃, β₀–β₃)</span>
          <span>3 (a₀, a₁, a₂)</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>Ionosphere model</span>
          <span>Single thin-shell at 350 km</span>
          <span>Full 3D electron density profile</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>STEC computation</span>
          <span>VTEC × mapping function</span>
          <span>Direct numerical integration</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>Typical correction quality</span>
          <span class="warn">~50% RMS reduction</span>
          <span class="ok">~60–70% RMS reduction</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>Performance at low latitudes</span>
          <span class="bad">Poor</span>
          <span class="warn">Moderate</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mc-row">
          <span>Computation complexity</span>
          <span class="good">Simple arithmetic</span>
          <span class="warn">Numerical integration</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="iono-free">The ionosphere-free combination</h2>
      <p>
        For dual-frequency receivers, ionospheric delay is eliminated entirely — not modelled
        but removed algebraically. Because the delay is proportional to 1/f², measurements
        on two frequencies can be combined to cancel it:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">ρ_IF = (f₁² · ρ₁ − f₂² · ρ₂) / (f₁² − f₂²)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          ρ_IF = ionosphere-free pseudorange (m)<br/>
          ρ₁, ρ₂ = pseudoranges on frequency f₁ and f₂ (m)<br/>
          f₁, f₂ = signal frequencies (Hz)<br/><br/>
          For GPS L1/L2: f₁ = 1575.42 MHz, f₂ = 1227.60 MHz<br/>
          Coefficients: α₁ = f₁²/(f₁²−f₂²) ≈ 2.546, α₂ = f₂²/(f₁²−f₂²) ≈ 1.546<br/>
          ρ_IF = 2.546·ρ₁ − 1.546·ρ₂<br/><br/>
          First-order ionospheric delay (the 40.3·TEC/f² term) is eliminated completely.
          Second-order terms remain but are typically &lt;1 cm.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Noise amplification</h3>
      <p>
        The ionosphere-free combination amplifies measurement noise by a factor that depends on
        the frequency ratio:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">σ_IF = √(α₁² + α₂²) · σ_single ≈ 2.98 · σ_single  (GPS L1/L2)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          For GPS L1/L5: f₁ = 1575.42 MHz, f₂ = 1176.45 MHz → noise factor ≈ 2.59<br/>
          The noise amplification is the price of eliminating the ionosphere.
          For a pseudorange noise of 0.3 m, the ionosphere-free combination has noise of ~0.9 m.
          This is still vastly better than the 5–30 m ionospheric delay it eliminates.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="if-tradeoff">
        <div class="if-col">
          <div class="if-title">Single frequency L1</div>
          <div class="if-errors">
            <div class="if-err err-bad">Ionosphere: 3 – 30 m ❌</div>
            <div class="if-err err-ok">Code noise: ~0.3 m</div>
          </div>
          <div class="if-total">Total error dominated by iono</div>
        </div>
        <div class="if-arrow">→ IF combination →</div>
        <div class="if-col">
          <div class="if-title">Dual frequency (IF)</div>
          <div class="if-errors">
            <div class="if-err err-good">Ionosphere: &lt;0.01 m ✓</div>
            <div class="if-err err-warn">IF noise: ~0.9 m (amplified)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="if-total">Noise-limited, not iono-limited</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="higher-order">Higher-order effects</h2>
      <p>
        The ionospheric delay expression I = 40.3·TEC/f² is the first-order approximation.
        Higher-order terms become significant for centimetre-level positioning:
      </p>

      <div class="higher-order-table">
        <div class="ho-row ho-header">
          <span>Order</span>
          <span>Term</span>
          <span>Magnitude (L1)</span>
          <span>Relevance</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ho-row">
          <span>1st</span>
          <span>40.3·TEC / f²</span>
          <span class="bad">~1–30 m</span>
          <span>Eliminated by IF combination</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ho-row">
          <span>2nd</span>
          <span>∝ TEC · B_geomagnetic / f³</span>
          <span class="warn">~1–10 cm</span>
          <span>Important for PPP at sub-cm level</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ho-row">
          <span>3rd</span>
          <span>∝ TEC² / f⁴</span>
          <span class="good">&lt;1 mm</span>
          <span>Negligible for most applications</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The second-order term depends on the Earth's magnetic field strength and orientation —
        it cannot be eliminated by the standard ionosphere-free combination. For geodetic
        applications requiring sub-centimetre accuracy, second-order ionospheric corrections
        are applied using geomagnetic field models (IGRF) and precise TEC maps.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Delay ∝ TEC/f²</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Ionospheric delay is proportional to Total Electron Content and inversely proportional to frequency squared. Code is delayed; carrier phase is advanced by the same magnitude.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Klobuchar — free, ~50% correction</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GPS broadcasts 8 Klobuchar coefficients. Half-cosine diurnal model. Corrects ~50% of RMS delay at mid-latitudes. Free, simple, but poor at equatorial latitudes and during storms.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🛰️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">NeQuick — Galileo's improvement</div>
          <div class="summary-body">3-coefficient 3D model with direct STEC integration. ~60–70% RMS correction. Better than Klobuchar, especially at low latitudes. Still single-frequency limited.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">2️⃣</div>
          <div class="summary-title">IF combination — full elimination</div>
          <div class="summary-body">ρ_IF = (f₁²·ρ₁ − f₂²·ρ₂)/(f₁²−f₂²). Eliminates first-order iono completely. Noise amplified ~3×. Still the best option — removes 30 m of error at the cost of 0.6 m of extra noise.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/ambiguity-resolution" class="nav-prev">← Ambiguity Resolution</a>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/coordinate-transforms" class="nav-next">Coordinate Transforms →</a>
      </div>

